28static PyObject *TestError; /* set to exception object in init */
29
30/* Raise TestError with test_name + ": " + msg, and return NULL. */
31
32static PyObject *
33raiseTestError(const char* test_name, const char* msg)
34{
35 PyErr_Format(TestError, "%s: %s", test_name, msg);
36 return NULL;
37}

39/* Test #defines from pyconfig.h (particularly the SIZEOF_* defines).
40
41 The ones derived from autoconf on the UNIX-like OSes can be relied
42 upon (in the absence of sloppy cross-compiling), but the Windows
43 platforms have these hardcoded. Better safe than sorry.
44*/
45static PyObject*
46sizeof_error(const char* fatname, const char* typname,
47 int expected, int got)
48{
49 PyErr_Format(TestError,
50 "%s #define == %d but sizeof(%s) == %d",
51 fatname, expected, typname, got);
52 return (PyObject*)NULL;
53}
54
55static PyObject*
56test_config(PyObject *self)
57{
58#define CHECK_SIZEOF(FATNAME, TYPE) \
59 if (FATNAME != sizeof(TYPE)) \
60 return sizeof_error(#FATNAME, #TYPE, FATNAME, sizeof(TYPE))
61
62 CHECK_SIZEOF(SIZEOF_SHORT, short);
63 CHECK_SIZEOF(SIZEOF_INT, int);
64 CHECK_SIZEOF(SIZEOF_LONG, long);
65 CHECK_SIZEOF(SIZEOF_VOID_P, void*);
66 CHECK_SIZEOF(SIZEOF_TIME_T, time_t);
67 CHECK_SIZEOF(SIZEOF_LONG_LONG, long long);
68
69#undef CHECK_SIZEOF
70
71 Py_RETURN_NONE;
72}

74static PyObject*
75test_sizeof_c_types(PyObject *self)
76{
77#if defined(__GNUC__) && ((__GNUC__ > 4) || ((__GNUC__ == 4) && (__GNUC_MINOR__ > 5)))
78#pragma GCC diagnostic push
79#pragma GCC diagnostic ignored "-Wtype-limits"
80#endif
81#define CHECK_SIZEOF(TYPE, EXPECTED) \
82 if (EXPECTED != sizeof(TYPE)) { \
83 PyErr_Format(TestError, \
84 "sizeof(%s) = %u instead of %u", \
85 #TYPE, sizeof(TYPE), EXPECTED); \
86 return (PyObject*)NULL; \
87 }
88#define IS_SIGNED(TYPE) (((TYPE)-1) < (TYPE)0)
89#define CHECK_SIGNNESS(TYPE, SIGNED) \
90 if (IS_SIGNED(TYPE) != SIGNED) { \
91 PyErr_Format(TestError, \
92 "%s signness is, instead of %i", \
93 #TYPE, IS_SIGNED(TYPE), SIGNED); \
94 return (PyObject*)NULL; \
95 }
96
97 /* integer types */
98 CHECK_SIZEOF(Py_UCS1, 1);
99 CHECK_SIZEOF(Py_UCS2, 2);
100 CHECK_SIZEOF(Py_UCS4, 4);
101 CHECK_SIGNNESS(Py_UCS1, 0);
102 CHECK_SIGNNESS(Py_UCS2, 0);
103 CHECK_SIGNNESS(Py_UCS4, 0);
104 CHECK_SIZEOF(int32_t, 4);
105 CHECK_SIGNNESS(int32_t, 1);
106 CHECK_SIZEOF(uint32_t, 4);
107 CHECK_SIGNNESS(uint32_t, 0);
108 CHECK_SIZEOF(int64_t, 8);
109 CHECK_SIGNNESS(int64_t, 1);
110 CHECK_SIZEOF(uint64_t, 8);
111 CHECK_SIGNNESS(uint64_t, 0);
112
113 /* pointer/size types */
114 CHECK_SIZEOF(size_t, sizeof(void *));
115 CHECK_SIGNNESS(size_t, 0);
116 CHECK_SIZEOF(Py_ssize_t, sizeof(void *));
117 CHECK_SIGNNESS(Py_ssize_t, 1);
118
119 CHECK_SIZEOF(uintptr_t, sizeof(void *));
120 CHECK_SIGNNESS(uintptr_t, 0);
121 CHECK_SIZEOF(intptr_t, sizeof(void *));
122 CHECK_SIGNNESS(intptr_t, 1);
123
124 Py_RETURN_NONE;
125
126#undef IS_SIGNED
127#undef CHECK_SIGNESS
128#undef CHECK_SIZEOF
129#if defined(__GNUC__) && ((__GNUC__ > 4) || ((__GNUC__ == 4) && (__GNUC_MINOR__ > 5)))
130#pragma GCC diagnostic pop
131#endif
132}

135static PyObject*
136test_list_api(PyObject *self)
137{
138 PyObject* list;
139 int i;
140
141 /* SF bug 132008: PyList_Reverse segfaults */
142#define NLIST 30
143 list = PyList_New(NLIST);
144 if (list == (PyObject*)NULL)
145 return (PyObject*)NULL;
146 /* list = range(NLIST) */
147 for (i = 0; i < NLIST; ++i) {
148 PyObject* anint = PyLong_FromLong(i);
149 if (anint == (PyObject*)NULL) {
150 Py_DECREF(list);
151 return (PyObject*)NULL;
152 }
153 PyList_SET_ITEM(list, i, anint);
154 }
155 /* list.reverse(), via PyList_Reverse() */
156 i = PyList_Reverse(list); /* should not blow up! */
157 if (i != 0) {
158 Py_DECREF(list);
159 return (PyObject*)NULL;
160 }
161 /* Check that list == range(29, -1, -1) now */
162 for (i = 0; i < NLIST; ++i) {
163 PyObject* anint = PyList_GET_ITEM(list, i);
164 if (PyLong_AS_LONG(anint) != NLIST-1-i) {
165 PyErr_SetString(TestError,
166 "test_list_api: reverse screwed up");
167 Py_DECREF(list);
168 return (PyObject*)NULL;
169 }
170 }
171 Py_DECREF(list);
172#undef NLIST
173
174 Py_RETURN_NONE;
175}

177static int
178test_dict_inner(int count)
179{
180 Py_ssize_t pos = 0, iterations = 0;
181 int i;
182 PyObject *dict = PyDict_New();
183 PyObject *v, *k;
184
185 if (dict == NULL)
186 return -1;
187
188 for (i = 0; i < count; i++) {
189 v = PyLong_FromLong(i);
190 if (v == NULL) {
191 return -1;
192 }
193 if (PyDict_SetItem(dict, v, v) < 0) {
194 Py_DECREF(v);
195 return -1;
196 }
197 Py_DECREF(v);
198 }
199
200 while (PyDict_Next(dict, &pos, &k, &v)) {
201 PyObject *o;
202 iterations++;
203
204 i = PyLong_AS_LONG(v) + 1;
205 o = PyLong_FromLong(i);
206 if (o == NULL)
207 return -1;
208 if (PyDict_SetItem(dict, k, o) < 0) {
209 Py_DECREF(o);
210 return -1;
211 }
212 Py_DECREF(o);
213 }
214
215 Py_DECREF(dict);
216
217 if (iterations != count) {
218 PyErr_SetString(
219 TestError,
220 "test_dict_iteration: dict iteration went wrong ");
221 return -1;
222 } else {
223 return 0;
224 }
225}
226
227static PyObject*
228test_dict_iteration(PyObject* self)
229{
230 int i;
231
232 for (i = 0; i < 200; i++) {
233 if (test_dict_inner(i) < 0) {
234 return NULL;
235 }
236 }
237
238 Py_RETURN_NONE;
239}

241static PyObject*
242dict_getitem_knownhash(PyObject *self, PyObject *args)
243{
244 PyObject *mp, *key, *result;
245 Py_ssize_t hash;
246
247 if (!PyArg_ParseTuple(args, "OOn:dict_getitem_knownhash",
248 &mp, &key, &hash)) {
249 return NULL;
250 }
251
252 result = _PyDict_GetItem_KnownHash(mp, key, (Py_hash_t)hash);
253 if (result == NULL && !PyErr_Occurred()) {
254 _PyErr_SetKeyError(key);
255 return NULL;
256 }
257
258 Py_XINCREF(result);
259 return result;
260}

262static PyObject*
263dict_hassplittable(PyObject *self, PyObject *arg)
264{
265 if (!PyDict_Check(arg)) {
266 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
267 "dict_hassplittable() argument must be dict, not '%s'",
268 arg->ob_type->tp_name);
269 return NULL;
270 }
271
272 return PyBool_FromLong(_PyDict_HasSplitTable((PyDictObject*)arg));
273}

312 0, /* tp_descr_set */

314 0, /* tp_init */
315 0, /* tp_alloc */
316 PyType_GenericNew, /* tp_new */

319static PyObject*
320test_lazy_hash_inheritance(PyObject* self)
321{
322 PyTypeObject *type;
323 PyObject *obj;
324 Py_hash_t hash;
325
326 type = &_HashInheritanceTester_Type;
327
328 if (type->tp_dict != NULL)
329 /* The type has already been initialized. This probably means
330 -R is being used. */
331 Py_RETURN_NONE;
332
333
334 obj = PyObject_New(PyObject, type);
335 if (obj == NULL) {
336 PyErr_Clear();
337 PyErr_SetString(
338 TestError,
339 "test_lazy_hash_inheritance: failed to create object");
340 return NULL;
341 }
342
343 if (type->tp_dict != NULL) {
344 PyErr_SetString(
345 TestError,
346 "test_lazy_hash_inheritance: type initialised too soon");
347 Py_DECREF(obj);
348 return NULL;
349 }
350
351 hash = PyObject_Hash(obj);
352 if ((hash == -1) && PyErr_Occurred()) {
353 PyErr_Clear();
354 PyErr_SetString(
355 TestError,
356 "test_lazy_hash_inheritance: could not hash object");
357 Py_DECREF(obj);
358 return NULL;
359 }
360
361 if (type->tp_dict == NULL) {
362 PyErr_SetString(
363 TestError,
364 "test_lazy_hash_inheritance: type not initialised by hash()");
365 Py_DECREF(obj);
366 return NULL;
367 }
368
369 if (type->tp_hash != PyType_Type.tp_hash) {
370 PyErr_SetString(
371 TestError,
372 "test_lazy_hash_inheritance: unexpected hash function");
373 Py_DECREF(obj);
374 return NULL;
375 }
376
377 Py_DECREF(obj);
378
379 Py_RETURN_NONE;
380}

383/* Tests of PyLong_{As, From}{Unsigned,}Long(), and
384 PyLong_{As, From}{Unsigned,}LongLong().
385
386 Note that the meat of the test is contained in testcapi_long.h.
387 This is revolting, but delicate code duplication is worse: "almost
388 exactly the same" code is needed to test long long, but the ubiquitous
389 dependence on type names makes it impossible to use a parameterized
390 function. A giant macro would be even worse than this. A C++ template
391 would be perfect.
392
393 The "report an error" functions are deliberately not part of the #include
394 file: if the test fails, you can set a breakpoint in the appropriate
395 error function directly, and crawl back from there in the debugger.
396*/
397
398#define UNBIND(X) Py_DECREF(X); (X) = NULL
399

401raise_test_long_error(const char* msg)
402{
403 return raiseTestError("test_long_api", msg);
404}

456/* Test the PyLong_AsLongAndOverflow API. General conversion to PY_LONG
457 is tested by test_long_api_inner. This test will concentrate on proper
458 handling of overflow.
459*/
460
461static PyObject *
462test_long_and_overflow(PyObject *self)
463{
464 PyObject *num, *one, *temp;
465 long value;
466 int overflow;
467
468 /* Test that overflow is set properly for a large value. */
469 /* num is a number larger than LONG_MAX even on 64-bit platforms */
470 num = PyLong_FromString("FFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF", NULL, 16);
471 if (num == NULL)
472 return NULL;
473 overflow = 1234;
474 value = PyLong_AsLongAndOverflow(num, &overflow);
475 Py_DECREF(num);
476 if (value == -1 && PyErr_Occurred())
477 return NULL;
478 if (value != -1)
479 return raiseTestError("test_long_and_overflow",
480 "return value was not set to -1");
481 if (overflow != 1)
482 return raiseTestError("test_long_and_overflow",
483 "overflow was not set to 1");
484
485 /* Same again, with num = LONG_MAX + 1 */
486 num = PyLong_FromLong(LONG_MAX);
487 if (num == NULL)
488 return NULL;
489 one = PyLong_FromLong(1L);
490 if (one == NULL) {
491 Py_DECREF(num);
492 return NULL;
493 }
494 temp = PyNumber_Add(num, one);
495 Py_DECREF(one);
496 Py_DECREF(num);
497 num = temp;
498 if (num == NULL)
499 return NULL;
500 overflow = 0;
501 value = PyLong_AsLongAndOverflow(num, &overflow);
502 Py_DECREF(num);
503 if (value == -1 && PyErr_Occurred())
504 return NULL;
505 if (value != -1)
506 return raiseTestError("test_long_and_overflow",
507 "return value was not set to -1");
508 if (overflow != 1)
509 return raiseTestError("test_long_and_overflow",
510 "overflow was not set to 1");
511
512 /* Test that overflow is set properly for a large negative value. */
513 /* num is a number smaller than LONG_MIN even on 64-bit platforms */
514 num = PyLong_FromString("-FFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF", NULL, 16);
515 if (num == NULL)
516 return NULL;
517 overflow = 1234;
518 value = PyLong_AsLongAndOverflow(num, &overflow);
519 Py_DECREF(num);
520 if (value == -1 && PyErr_Occurred())
521 return NULL;
522 if (value != -1)
523 return raiseTestError("test_long_and_overflow",
524 "return value was not set to -1");
525 if (overflow != -1)
526 return raiseTestError("test_long_and_overflow",
527 "overflow was not set to -1");
528
529 /* Same again, with num = LONG_MIN - 1 */
530 num = PyLong_FromLong(LONG_MIN);
531 if (num == NULL)
532 return NULL;
533 one = PyLong_FromLong(1L);
534 if (one == NULL) {
535 Py_DECREF(num);
536 return NULL;
537 }
538 temp = PyNumber_Subtract(num, one);
539 Py_DECREF(one);
540 Py_DECREF(num);
541 num = temp;
542 if (num == NULL)
543 return NULL;
544 overflow = 0;
545 value = PyLong_AsLongAndOverflow(num, &overflow);
546 Py_DECREF(num);
547 if (value == -1 && PyErr_Occurred())
548 return NULL;
549 if (value != -1)
550 return raiseTestError("test_long_and_overflow",
551 "return value was not set to -1");
552 if (overflow != -1)
553 return raiseTestError("test_long_and_overflow",
554 "overflow was not set to -1");
555
556 /* Test that overflow is cleared properly for small values. */
557 num = PyLong_FromString("FF", NULL, 16);
558 if (num == NULL)
559 return NULL;
560 overflow = 1234;
561 value = PyLong_AsLongAndOverflow(num, &overflow);
562 Py_DECREF(num);
563 if (value == -1 && PyErr_Occurred())
564 return NULL;
565 if (value != 0xFF)
566 return raiseTestError("test_long_and_overflow",
567 "expected return value 0xFF");
568 if (overflow != 0)
569 return raiseTestError("test_long_and_overflow",
570 "overflow was not cleared");
571
572 num = PyLong_FromString("-FF", NULL, 16);
573 if (num == NULL)
574 return NULL;
575 overflow = 0;
576 value = PyLong_AsLongAndOverflow(num, &overflow);
577 Py_DECREF(num);
578 if (value == -1 && PyErr_Occurred())
579 return NULL;
580 if (value != -0xFF)
581 return raiseTestError("test_long_and_overflow",
582 "expected return value 0xFF");
583 if (overflow != 0)
584 return raiseTestError("test_long_and_overflow",
585 "overflow was set incorrectly");
586
587 num = PyLong_FromLong(LONG_MAX);
588 if (num == NULL)
589 return NULL;
590 overflow = 1234;
591 value = PyLong_AsLongAndOverflow(num, &overflow);
592 Py_DECREF(num);
593 if (value == -1 && PyErr_Occurred())
594 return NULL;
595 if (value != LONG_MAX)
596 return raiseTestError("test_long_and_overflow",
597 "expected return value LONG_MAX");
598 if (overflow != 0)
599 return raiseTestError("test_long_and_overflow",
600 "overflow was not cleared");
601
602 num = PyLong_FromLong(LONG_MIN);
603 if (num == NULL)
604 return NULL;
605 overflow = 0;
606 value = PyLong_AsLongAndOverflow(num, &overflow);
607 Py_DECREF(num);
608 if (value == -1 && PyErr_Occurred())
609 return NULL;
610 if (value != LONG_MIN)
611 return raiseTestError("test_long_and_overflow",
612 "expected return value LONG_MIN");
613 if (overflow != 0)
614 return raiseTestError("test_long_and_overflow",
615 "overflow was not cleared");
616
617 Py_RETURN_NONE;
618}

620/* Test the PyLong_AsLongLongAndOverflow API. General conversion to
621 long long is tested by test_long_api_inner. This test will
622 concentrate on proper handling of overflow.
623*/

625static PyObject *
626test_long_long_and_overflow(PyObject *self)
627{

751 num = PyLong_FromLongLong(PY_LLONG_MAX);

754 overflow = 1234;
755 value = PyLong_AsLongLongAndOverflow(num, &overflow);
756 Py_DECREF(num);
757 if (value == -1 && PyErr_Occurred())
758 return NULL;
759 if (value != PY_LLONG_MAX)
760 return raiseTestError("test_long_long_and_overflow",
761 "expected return value PY_LLONG_MAX");
762 if (overflow != 0)
763 return raiseTestError("test_long_long_and_overflow",
764 "overflow was not cleared");
765
766 num = PyLong_FromLongLong(PY_LLONG_MIN);
767 if (num == NULL)
768 return NULL;
769 overflow = 0;
770 value = PyLong_AsLongLongAndOverflow(num, &overflow);
771 Py_DECREF(num);
772 if (value == -1 && PyErr_Occurred())
773 return NULL;
774 if (value != PY_LLONG_MIN)
775 return raiseTestError("test_long_long_and_overflow",
776 "expected return value PY_LLONG_MIN");
777 if (overflow != 0)
778 return raiseTestError("test_long_long_and_overflow",
779 "overflow was not cleared");
780
781 Py_RETURN_NONE;
782}

784/* Test the PyLong_As{Size,Ssize}_t API. At present this just tests that
785 non-integer arguments are handled correctly. It should be extended to
786 test overflow handling.
787 */
788
789static PyObject *
790test_long_as_size_t(PyObject *self)
791{
792 size_t out_u;
793 Py_ssize_t out_s;
794
795 Py_INCREF(Py_None);
796
797 out_u = PyLong_AsSize_t(Py_None);
798 if (out_u != (size_t)-1 || !PyErr_Occurred())
799 return raiseTestError("test_long_as_size_t",
800 "PyLong_AsSize_t(None) didn't complain");
801 if (!PyErr_ExceptionMatches(PyExc_TypeError))
802 return raiseTestError("test_long_as_size_t",
803 "PyLong_AsSize_t(None) raised "
804 "something other than TypeError");
805 PyErr_Clear();
806
807 out_s = PyLong_AsSsize_t(Py_None);
808 if (out_s != (Py_ssize_t)-1 || !PyErr_Occurred())
809 return raiseTestError("test_long_as_size_t",
810 "PyLong_AsSsize_t(None) didn't complain");
811 if (!PyErr_ExceptionMatches(PyExc_TypeError))
812 return raiseTestError("test_long_as_size_t",
813 "PyLong_AsSsize_t(None) raised "
814 "something other than TypeError");
815 PyErr_Clear();
816
817 /* Py_INCREF(Py_None) omitted - we already have a reference to it. */
818 return Py_None;
819}

846/* Test the L code for PyArg_ParseTuple. This should deliver a long long
847 for both long and int arguments. The test may leak a little memory if
848 it fails.
849*/
850static PyObject *
851test_L_code(PyObject *self)
852{
853 PyObject *tuple, *num;
854 long long value;
855
856 tuple = PyTuple_New(1);
857 if (tuple == NULL)
858 return NULL;
859
860 num = PyLong_FromLong(42);
861 if (num == NULL)
862 return NULL;
863
864 PyTuple_SET_ITEM(tuple, 0, num);
865
866 value = -1;
867 if (PyArg_ParseTuple(tuple, "L:test_L_code", &value) < 0)
868 return NULL;
869 if (value != 42)
870 return raiseTestError("test_L_code",
871 "L code returned wrong value for long 42");
872
873 Py_DECREF(num);
874 num = PyLong_FromLong(42);
875 if (num == NULL)
876 return NULL;
877
878 PyTuple_SET_ITEM(tuple, 0, num);
879
880 value = -1;
881 if (PyArg_ParseTuple(tuple, "L:test_L_code", &value) < 0)
882 return NULL;
883 if (value != 42)
884 return raiseTestError("test_L_code",
885 "L code returned wrong value for int 42");
886
887 Py_DECREF(tuple);
888 Py_RETURN_NONE;
889}

904static int
905test_buildvalue_N_error(const char *fmt)
906{
907 PyObject *arg, *res;
908
909 arg = PyList_New(0);
910 if (arg == NULL) {
911 return -1;
912 }
913
914 Py_INCREF(arg);
915 res = Py_BuildValue(fmt, return_none, NULL, arg);
916 if (res == NULL) {
917 return -1;
918 }
919 Py_DECREF(res);
920 if (Py_REFCNT(arg) != 1) {
921 PyErr_Format(TestError, "test_buildvalue_N: "
922 "arg was not decrefed in successful "
923 "Py_BuildValue(\"%s\")", fmt);
924 return -1;
925 }
926
927 Py_INCREF(arg);
928 res = Py_BuildValue(fmt, raise_error, NULL, arg);
929 if (res != NULL || !PyErr_Occurred()) {
930 PyErr_Format(TestError, "test_buildvalue_N: "
931 "Py_BuildValue(\"%s\") didn't complain", fmt);
932 return -1;
933 }
934 PyErr_Clear();
935 if (Py_REFCNT(arg) != 1) {
936 PyErr_Format(TestError, "test_buildvalue_N: "
937 "arg was not decrefed in failed "
938 "Py_BuildValue(\"%s\")", fmt);
939 return -1;
940 }
941 Py_DECREF(arg);
942 return 0;
943}
944
945static PyObject *
946test_buildvalue_N(PyObject *self, PyObject *noargs)
947{
948 PyObject *arg, *res;
949
950 arg = PyList_New(0);
951 if (arg == NULL) {
952 return NULL;
953 }
954 Py_INCREF(arg);
955 res = Py_BuildValue("N", arg);
956 if (res == NULL) {
957 return NULL;
958 }
959 if (res != arg) {
960 return raiseTestError("test_buildvalue_N",
961 "Py_BuildValue(\"N\") returned wrong result");
962 }
963 if (Py_REFCNT(arg) != 2) {
964 return raiseTestError("test_buildvalue_N",
965 "arg was not decrefed in Py_BuildValue(\"N\")");
966 }
967 Py_DECREF(res);
968 Py_DECREF(arg);
969
970 if (test_buildvalue_N_error("O&N") < 0)
971 return NULL;
972 if (test_buildvalue_N_error("(O&N)") < 0)
973 return NULL;
974 if (test_buildvalue_N_error("[O&N]") < 0)
975 return NULL;
976 if (test_buildvalue_N_error("{O&N}") < 0)
977 return NULL;
978 if (test_buildvalue_N_error("{()O&(())N}") < 0)
979 return NULL;
980
981 Py_RETURN_NONE;
982}

1173/* This function not only tests the 'k' getargs code, but also the
1174 PyLong_AsUnsignedLongMask() function. */
1175static PyObject *
1176test_k_code(PyObject *self)
1177{
1178 PyObject *tuple, *num;
1179 unsigned long value;
1180
1181 tuple = PyTuple_New(1);
1182 if (tuple == NULL)
1183 return NULL;
1184
1185 /* a number larger than ULONG_MAX even on 64-bit platforms */
1186 num = PyLong_FromString("FFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF", NULL, 16);
1187 if (num == NULL)
1188 return NULL;
1189
1190 value = PyLong_AsUnsignedLongMask(num);
1191 if (value != ULONG_MAX)
1192 return raiseTestError("test_k_code",
1193 "PyLong_AsUnsignedLongMask() returned wrong value for long 0xFFF...FFF");
1194
1195 PyTuple_SET_ITEM(tuple, 0, num);
1196
1197 value = 0;
1198 if (PyArg_ParseTuple(tuple, "k:test_k_code", &value) < 0)
1199 return NULL;
1200 if (value != ULONG_MAX)
1201 return raiseTestError("test_k_code",
1202 "k code returned wrong value for long 0xFFF...FFF");
1203
1204 Py_DECREF(num);
1205 num = PyLong_FromString("-FFFFFFFF000000000000000042", NULL, 16);
1206 if (num == NULL)
1207 return NULL;
1208
1209 value = PyLong_AsUnsignedLongMask(num);
1210 if (value != (unsigned long)-0x42)
1211 return raiseTestError("test_k_code",
1212 "PyLong_AsUnsignedLongMask() returned wrong "
1213 "value for long -0xFFF..000042");
1214
1215 PyTuple_SET_ITEM(tuple, 0, num);
1216
1217 value = 0;
1218 if (PyArg_ParseTuple(tuple, "k:test_k_code", &value) < 0)
1219 return NULL;
1220 if (value != (unsigned long)-0x42)
1221 return raiseTestError("test_k_code",
1222 "k code returned wrong value for long -0xFFF..000042");
1223
1224 Py_DECREF(tuple);
1225 Py_RETURN_NONE;
1226}

1483static PyObject *
1484getargs_es_hash(PyObject *self, PyObject *args)
1485{
1486 PyObject *arg, *result;
1487 const char *encoding = NULL;
1488 PyByteArrayObject *buffer = NULL;
1489 char *str = NULL;
1490 Py_ssize_t size;
1491
1492 if (!PyArg_ParseTuple(args, "O|sY", &arg, &encoding, &buffer))
1493 return NULL;
1494 if (buffer != NULL) {
1495 str = PyByteArray_AS_STRING(buffer);
1496 size = PyByteArray_GET_SIZE(buffer);
1497 }
1498 if (!PyArg_Parse(arg, "es#", encoding, &str, &size))
1499 return NULL;
1500 result = PyBytes_FromStringAndSize(str, size);

1562static PyObject *
1563parse_tuple_and_keywords(PyObject *self, PyObject *args)
1564{
1565 PyObject *sub_args;
1566 PyObject *sub_kwargs;
1567 const char *sub_format;
1568 PyObject *sub_keywords;
1569
1570 Py_ssize_t i, size;
1571 char *keywords[8 + 1]; /* space for NULL at end */
1572 PyObject *o;
1573 PyObject *converted[8];
1574
1575 int result;
1576 PyObject *return_value = NULL;
1577
1578 double buffers[8][4]; /* double ensures alignment where necessary */
1579
1580 if (!PyArg_ParseTuple(args, "OOsO:parse_tuple_and_keywords",
1581 &sub_args, &sub_kwargs,
1582 &sub_format, &sub_keywords))
1583 return NULL;
1584
1585 if (!(PyList_CheckExact(sub_keywords) || PyTuple_CheckExact(sub_keywords))) {
1586 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_ValueError,
1587 "parse_tuple_and_keywords: sub_keywords must be either list or tuple");
1588 return NULL;
1589 }
1590
1591 memset(buffers, 0, sizeof(buffers));
1592 memset(converted, 0, sizeof(converted));
1593 memset(keywords, 0, sizeof(keywords));
1594
1595 size = PySequence_Fast_GET_SIZE(sub_keywords);
1596 if (size > 8) {
1597 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_ValueError,
1598 "parse_tuple_and_keywords: too many keywords in sub_keywords");
1599 goto exit;
1600 }
1601
1602 for (i = 0; i < size; i++) {
1603 o = PySequence_Fast_GET_ITEM(sub_keywords, i);
1604 if (!PyUnicode_FSConverter(o, (void *)(converted + i))) {
1605 PyErr_Format(PyExc_ValueError,
1606 "parse_tuple_and_keywords: could not convert keywords[%zd] to narrow string", i);
1607 goto exit;
1608 }
1609 keywords[i] = PyBytes_AS_STRING(converted[i]);
1610 }
1611
1612 result = PyArg_ParseTupleAndKeywords(sub_args, sub_kwargs,
1613 sub_format, keywords,
1614 buffers + 0, buffers + 1, buffers + 2, buffers + 3,
1615 buffers + 4, buffers + 5, buffers + 6, buffers + 7);
1616
1617 if (result) {
1618 return_value = Py_None;
1619 Py_INCREF(Py_None);
1620 }
1621
1622exit:
1623 size = sizeof(converted) / sizeof(converted[0]);
1624 for (i = 0; i < size; i++) {
1625 Py_XDECREF(converted[i]);
1626 }
1627 return return_value;
1628}

1728static PyObject *
1729test_widechar(PyObject *self)
1730{
1731#if defined(SIZEOF_WCHAR_T) && (SIZEOF_WCHAR_T == 4)
1732 const wchar_t wtext[2] = {(wchar_t)0x10ABCDu};
1733 size_t wtextlen = 1;
1734 const wchar_t invalid[1] = {(wchar_t)0x110000u};
1735#else
1736 const wchar_t wtext[3] = {(wchar_t)0xDBEAu, (wchar_t)0xDFCDu};
1737 size_t wtextlen = 2;
1738#endif
1739 PyObject *wide, *utf8;
1740
1741 wide = PyUnicode_FromWideChar(wtext, wtextlen);
1742 if (wide == NULL)
1743 return NULL;
1744
1745 utf8 = PyUnicode_FromString("\xf4\x8a\xaf\x8d");
1746 if (utf8 == NULL) {
1747 Py_DECREF(wide);
1748 return NULL;
1749 }
1750
1751 if (PyUnicode_GET_LENGTH(wide) != PyUnicode_GET_LENGTH(utf8)) {
1752 Py_DECREF(wide);
1753 Py_DECREF(utf8);
1754 return raiseTestError("test_widechar",
1755 "wide string and utf8 string "
1756 "have different length");
1757 }
1758 if (PyUnicode_Compare(wide, utf8)) {
1759 Py_DECREF(wide);
1760 Py_DECREF(utf8);
1761 if (PyErr_Occurred())
1762 return NULL;
1763 return raiseTestError("test_widechar",
1764 "wide string and utf8 string "
1765 "are different");
1766 }
1767
1768 Py_DECREF(wide);
1769 Py_DECREF(utf8);
1770
1771#if defined(SIZEOF_WCHAR_T) && (SIZEOF_WCHAR_T == 4)
1772 wide = PyUnicode_FromWideChar(invalid, 1);
1773 if (wide == NULL)
1774 PyErr_Clear();
1775 else
1776 return raiseTestError("test_widechar",
1777 "PyUnicode_FromWideChar(L\"\\U00110000\", 1) didn't fail");
1778
1779 wide = PyUnicode_FromUnicode(invalid, 1);
1780 if (wide == NULL)
1781 PyErr_Clear();
1782 else
1783 return raiseTestError("test_widechar",
1784 "PyUnicode_FromUnicode(L\"\\U00110000\", 1) didn't fail");
1785
1786 wide = PyUnicode_FromUnicode(NULL, 1);
1787 if (wide == NULL)
1788 return NULL;
1789 PyUnicode_AS_UNICODE(wide)[0] = invalid[0];
1790 if (_PyUnicode_Ready(wide) < 0) {
1791 Py_DECREF(wide);
1792 PyErr_Clear();
1793 }
1794 else {
1795 Py_DECREF(wide);
1796 return raiseTestError("test_widechar",
1797 "PyUnicode_Ready() didn't fail");
1798 }
1799#endif
1800
1801 Py_RETURN_NONE;
1802}

1804static PyObject *
1805unicode_aswidechar(PyObject *self, PyObject *args)
1806{
1807 PyObject *unicode, *result;
1808 Py_ssize_t buflen, size;
1809 wchar_t *buffer;
1810
1811 if (!PyArg_ParseTuple(args, "Un", &unicode, &buflen))
1812 return NULL;
1813 buffer = PyMem_New(wchar_t, buflen);
1814 if (buffer == NULL)
1815 return PyErr_NoMemory();
1816
1817 size = PyUnicode_AsWideChar(unicode, buffer, buflen);
1818 if (size == -1) {
1819 PyMem_Free(buffer);
1820 return NULL;
1821 }
1822
1823 if (size < buflen)
1824 buflen = size + 1;
1825 else
1826 buflen = size;
1827 result = PyUnicode_FromWideChar(buffer, buflen);
1828 PyMem_Free(buffer);
1829 if (result == NULL)
1830 return NULL;
1831
1832 return Py_BuildValue("(Nn)", result, size);
1833}

1877 PyMem_FREE(buffer);

1908unicode_copycharacters(PyObject *self, PyObject *args)
1909{

1936static PyObject *
1937unicode_encodedecimal(PyObject *self, PyObject *args)
1938{
1939 Py_UNICODE *unicode;
1940 Py_ssize_t length;
1941 char *errors = NULL;
1942 PyObject *decimal;
1943 Py_ssize_t decimal_length, new_length;
1944 int res;
1945
1946 if (!PyArg_ParseTuple(args, "u#|s", &unicode, &length, &errors))
1947 return NULL;
1948
1949 decimal_length = length * 7; /* len('&#8364;') */
1950 decimal = PyBytes_FromStringAndSize(NULL, decimal_length);
1951 if (decimal == NULL)
1952 return NULL;
1953
1954 res = PyUnicode_EncodeDecimal(unicode, length,
1955 PyBytes_AS_STRING(decimal),
1956 errors);
1957 if (res < 0) {
1958 Py_DECREF(decimal);
1959 return NULL;
1960 }
1961
1962 new_length = strlen(PyBytes_AS_STRING(decimal));
1963 assert(new_length <= decimal_length);
1964 res = _PyBytes_Resize(&decimal, new_length);
1965 if (res < 0)
1966 return NULL;
1967
1968 return decimal;
1969}

2073/* Simple test of _PyLong_NumBits and _PyLong_Sign. */
2074static PyObject *
2075test_long_numbits(PyObject *self)
2076{
2077 struct triple {
2078 long input;
2079 size_t nbits;
2080 int sign;
2081 } testcases[] = {{0, 0, 0},
2082 {1L, 1, 1},
2083 {-1L, 1, -1},
2084 {2L, 2, 1},
2085 {-2L, 2, -1},
2086 {3L, 2, 1},
2087 {-3L, 2, -1},
2088 {4L, 3, 1},
2089 {-4L, 3, -1},
2090 {0x7fffL, 15, 1}, /* one Python int digit */
2091 {-0x7fffL, 15, -1},
2092 {0xffffL, 16, 1},
2093 {-0xffffL, 16, -1},
2094 {0xfffffffL, 28, 1},
2095 {-0xfffffffL, 28, -1}};
2096 size_t i;
2097
2098 for (i = 0; i < Py_ARRAY_LENGTH(testcases); ++i) {
2099 size_t nbits;
2100 int sign;
2101 PyObject *plong;
2102
2103 plong = PyLong_FromLong(testcases[i].input);
2104 if (plong == NULL)
2105 return NULL;
2106 nbits = _PyLong_NumBits(plong);
2107 sign = _PyLong_Sign(plong);
2108
2109 Py_DECREF(plong);
2110 if (nbits != testcases[i].nbits)
2111 return raiseTestError("test_long_numbits",
2112 "wrong result for _PyLong_NumBits");
2113 if (sign != testcases[i].sign)
2114 return raiseTestError("test_long_numbits",
2115 "wrong result for _PyLong_Sign");
2116 }
2117 Py_RETURN_NONE;
2118}

2132static PyObject *
2133raise_exception(PyObject *self, PyObject *args)
2134{
2135 PyObject *exc;
2136 PyObject *exc_args, *v;
2137 int num_args, i;
2138
2139 if (!PyArg_ParseTuple(args, "Oi:raise_exception",
2140 &exc, &num_args))
2141 return NULL;
2142
2143 exc_args = PyTuple_New(num_args);
2144 if (exc_args == NULL)
2145 return NULL;
2146 for (i = 0; i < num_args; ++i) {

2153 }
2154 PyErr_SetObject(exc, exc_args);

2221/* test_thread_state spawns a thread of its own, and that thread releases
2222 * `thread_done` when it's finished. The driver code has to know when the
2223 * thread finishes, because the thread uses a PyObject (the callable) that
2224 * may go away when the driver finishes. The former lack of this explicit
2225 * synchronization caused rare segfaults, so rare that they were seen only
2226 * on a Mac buildbot (although they were possible on any box).
2227 */
2228static PyThread_type_lock thread_done = NULL;
2229
2230static int
2231_make_call(void *callable)
2232{
2233 PyObject *rc;
2234 int success;
2235 PyGILState_STATE s = PyGILState_Ensure();
2236 rc = _PyObject_CallNoArg((PyObject *)callable);
2237 success = (rc != NULL);
2238 Py_XDECREF(rc);
2239 PyGILState_Release(s);
2240 return success;
2241}
2242
2243/* Same thing, but releases `thread_done` when it returns. This variant
2244 * should be called only from threads spawned by test_thread_state().
2245 */
2246static void
2247_make_call_from_thread(void *callable)
2248{
2249 _make_call(callable);
2250 PyThread_release_lock(thread_done);
2251}
2252
2253static PyObject *
2254test_thread_state(PyObject *self, PyObject *args)
2255{
2256 PyObject *fn;
2257 int success = 1;
2258
2259 if (!PyArg_ParseTuple(args, "O:test_thread_state", &fn))
2260 return NULL;
2261
2262 if (!PyCallable_Check(fn)) {
2263 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError, "'%s' object is not callable",
2264 fn->ob_type->tp_name);
2265 return NULL;
2266 }
2267
2268 /* Ensure Python is set up for threading */
2269 PyEval_InitThreads();
2270 thread_done = PyThread_allocate_lock();
2271 if (thread_done == NULL)
2272 return PyErr_NoMemory();
2273 PyThread_acquire_lock(thread_done, 1);
2274
2275 /* Start a new thread with our callback. */
2276 PyThread_start_new_thread(_make_call_from_thread, fn);
2277 /* Make the callback with the thread lock held by this thread */
2278 success &= _make_call(fn);
2279 /* Do it all again, but this time with the thread-lock released */
2280 Py_BEGIN_ALLOW_THREADS
2281 success &= _make_call(fn);
2282 PyThread_acquire_lock(thread_done, 1); /* wait for thread to finish */
2283 Py_END_ALLOW_THREADS
2284
2285 /* And once more with and without a thread
2286 XXX - should use a lock and work out exactly what we are trying
2287 to test <wink>
2288 */
2289 Py_BEGIN_ALLOW_THREADS
2290 PyThread_start_new_thread(_make_call_from_thread, fn);
2291 success &= _make_call(fn);
2292 PyThread_acquire_lock(thread_done, 1); /* wait for thread to finish */
2293 Py_END_ALLOW_THREADS
2294
2295 /* Release lock we acquired above. This is required on HP-UX. */
2296 PyThread_release_lock(thread_done);
2297
2298 PyThread_free_lock(thread_done);
2299 if (!success)
2300 return NULL;
2301 Py_RETURN_NONE;
2302}

2304/* test Py_AddPendingCalls using threads */
2305static int _pending_callback(void *arg)
2306{
2307 /* we assume the argument is callable object to which we own a reference */
2308 PyObject *callable = (PyObject *)arg;
2309 PyObject *r = _PyObject_CallNoArg(callable);
2310 Py_DECREF(callable);
2311 Py_XDECREF(r);
2312 return r != NULL ? 0 : -1;
2313}
2314
2315/* The following requests n callbacks to _pending_callback. It can be
2316 * run from any python thread.
2317 */
2318PyObject *pending_threadfunc(PyObject *self, PyObject *arg)
2319{
2320 PyObject *callable;
2321 int r;
2322 if (PyArg_ParseTuple(arg, "O", &callable) == 0)
2323 return NULL;
2324
2325 /* create the reference for the callbackwhile we hold the lock */
2326 Py_INCREF(callable);
2327
2328 Py_BEGIN_ALLOW_THREADS
2329 r = Py_AddPendingCall(&_pending_callback, callable);
2330 Py_END_ALLOW_THREADS
2331
2332 if (r<0) {
2333 Py_DECREF(callable); /* unsuccessful add, destroy the extra reference */
2334 Py_RETURN_FALSE;
2335 }
2336 Py_RETURN_TRUE;
2337}

2460

2462capsule_destructor(PyObject *o) {
2463 capsule_destructor_call_count++;

2465 capsule_error = "context did not match in destructor!";
2466 } else if (PyCapsule_GetDestructor(o) != capsule_destructor) {

2468 } else if (PyCapsule_GetName(o) != capsule_name) {
2469 capsule_error = "name did not match in destructor!";
2470 } else if (PyCapsule_GetPointer(o, capsule_name) != capsule_pointer) {
2471 capsule_error = "pointer did not match in destructor!";
2472 }
2473}

2931 goto error;
2932
2933 Py_RETURN_NONE;
2934
2935error:
2936 PyErr_SetString(TestError,
2937 "test_pep3118_obsolete_write_locks: failure");
2938 return NULL;
2939}

2969/* To run some code in a sub-interpreter. */
2970static PyObject *
2971run_in_subinterp(PyObject *self, PyObject *args)
2972{
2973 const char *code;
2974 int r;
2975 PyThreadState *substate, *mainstate;
2976
2977 if (!PyArg_ParseTuple(args, "s:run_in_subinterp",
2978 &code))
2979 return NULL;
2980
2981 mainstate = PyThreadState_Get();
2982
2983 PyThreadState_Swap(NULL);
2984
2985 substate = Py_NewInterpreter();
2986 if (substate == NULL) {
2987 /* Since no new thread state was created, there is no exception to
2988 propagate; raise a fresh one after swapping in the old thread
2989 state. */
2990 PyThreadState_Swap(mainstate);
2991 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError, "sub-interpreter creation failed");
2992 return NULL;
2993 }
2994 r = PyRun_SimpleString(code);
2995 Py_EndInterpreter(substate);
2996
2997 PyThreadState_Swap(mainstate);
2998
2999 return PyLong_FromLong(r);
3000}

3061static void
3062slot_tp_del(PyObject *self)
3063{
3064 _Py_IDENTIFIER(__tp_del__);
3065 PyObject *del, *res;
3066 PyObject *error_type, *error_value, *error_traceback;
3067
3068 /* Temporarily resurrect the object. */
3069 assert(self->ob_refcnt == 0);
3070 self->ob_refcnt = 1;
3071
3072 /* Save the current exception, if any. */
3073 PyErr_Fetch(&error_type, &error_value, &error_traceback);
3074
3075 /* Execute __del__ method, if any. */
3076 del = _PyObject_LookupSpecial(self, &PyId___tp_del__);
3077 if (del != NULL) {
3078 res = _PyObject_CallNoArg(del);
3079 if (res == NULL)
3080 PyErr_WriteUnraisable(del);
3081 else
3082 Py_DECREF(res);
3083 Py_DECREF(del);
3084 }
3085
3086 /* Restore the saved exception. */
3087 PyErr_Restore(error_type, error_value, error_traceback);
3088
3089 /* Undo the temporary resurrection; can't use DECREF here, it would
3090 * cause a recursive call.
3091 */
3092 assert(self->ob_refcnt > 0);
3093 if (--self->ob_refcnt == 0)
3094 return; /* this is the normal path out */
3095
3096 /* __del__ resurrected it! Make it look like the original Py_DECREF
3097 * never happened.
3098 */
3099 {
3100 Py_ssize_t refcnt = self->ob_refcnt;
3101 _Py_NewReference(self);
3102 self->ob_refcnt = refcnt;
3103 }
3104 assert(!PyType_IS_GC(Py_TYPE(self)) ||
3105 _Py_AS_GC(self)->gc.gc_refs != _PyGC_REFS_UNTRACKED);
3106 /* If Py_REF_DEBUG, _Py_NewReference bumped _Py_RefTotal, so
3107 * we need to undo that. */
3108 _Py_DEC_REFTOTAL;
3109 /* If Py_TRACE_REFS, _Py_NewReference re-added self to the object
3110 * chain, so no more to do there.
3111 * If COUNT_ALLOCS, the original decref bumped tp_frees, and
3112 * _Py_NewReference bumped tp_allocs: both of those need to be
3113 * undone.
3114 */
3115#ifdef COUNT_ALLOCS
3116 --Py_TYPE(self)->tp_frees;
3117 --Py_TYPE(self)->tp_allocs;
3118#endif
3119}

3121static PyObject *
3122with_tp_del(PyObject *self, PyObject *args)
3123{
3124 PyObject *obj;
3125 PyTypeObject *tp;
3126
3127 if (!PyArg_ParseTuple(args, "O:with_tp_del", &obj))
3128 return NULL;
3129 tp = (PyTypeObject *) obj;

3131 PyErr_Format(PyExc_TypeError,
3132 "heap type expected, got %R", obj);
3133 return NULL;
3134 }
3135 tp->tp_del = slot_tp_del;
3136 Py_INCREF(obj);
3137 return obj;
3138}

3299static PyObject *
3300test_setallocators(PyMemAllocatorDomain domain)
3301{
3302 PyObject *res = NULL;
3303 const char *error_msg;
3304 alloc_hook_t hook;
3305 PyMemAllocatorEx alloc;
3306 size_t size, size2, nelem, elsize;
3307 void *ptr, *ptr2;
3308
3309 memset(&hook, 0, sizeof(hook));
3310
3311 alloc.ctx = &hook;
3312 alloc.malloc = &hook_malloc;
3313 alloc.calloc = &hook_calloc;
3314 alloc.realloc = &hook_realloc;
3315 alloc.free = &hook_free;
3316 PyMem_GetAllocator(domain, &hook.alloc);
3317 PyMem_SetAllocator(domain, &alloc);
3318
3319 size = 42;
3320 switch(domain)
3321 {
3322 case PYMEM_DOMAIN_RAW: ptr = PyMem_RawMalloc(size); break;
3323 case PYMEM_DOMAIN_MEM: ptr = PyMem_Malloc(size); break;
3324 case PYMEM_DOMAIN_OBJ: ptr = PyObject_Malloc(size); break;
3325 default: ptr = NULL; break;
3326 }
3327
3328 if (ptr == NULL) {
3329 error_msg = "malloc failed";
3330 goto fail;
3331 }
3332
3333 if (hook.malloc_size != size) {
3334 error_msg = "malloc invalid size";
3335 goto fail;
3336 }
3337
3338 size2 = 200;
3339 switch(domain)
3340 {
3341 case PYMEM_DOMAIN_RAW: ptr2 = PyMem_RawRealloc(ptr, size2); break;
3342 case PYMEM_DOMAIN_MEM: ptr2 = PyMem_Realloc(ptr, size2); break;
3343 case PYMEM_DOMAIN_OBJ: ptr2 = PyObject_Realloc(ptr, size2); break;
3344 default: ptr2 = NULL; break;
3345 }
3346
3347 if (ptr2 == NULL) {
3348 error_msg = "realloc failed";
3349 goto fail;
3350 }
3351
3352 if (hook.realloc_ptr != ptr
3353 || hook.realloc_new_size != size2) {
3354 error_msg = "realloc invalid parameters";
3355 goto fail;
3356 }
3357
3358 switch(domain)
3359 {
3360 case PYMEM_DOMAIN_RAW: PyMem_RawFree(ptr2); break;
3361 case PYMEM_DOMAIN_MEM: PyMem_Free(ptr2); break;
3362 case PYMEM_DOMAIN_OBJ: PyObject_Free(ptr2); break;
3363 }
3364
3365 if (hook.free_ptr != ptr2) {
3366 error_msg = "free invalid pointer";
3367 goto fail;
3368 }
3369
3370 nelem = 2;
3371 elsize = 5;
3372 switch(domain)
3373 {
3374 case PYMEM_DOMAIN_RAW: ptr = PyMem_RawCalloc(nelem, elsize); break;
3375 case PYMEM_DOMAIN_MEM: ptr = PyMem_Calloc(nelem, elsize); break;
3376 case PYMEM_DOMAIN_OBJ: ptr = PyObject_Calloc(nelem, elsize); break;
3377 default: ptr = NULL; break;
3378 }
3379
3380 if (ptr == NULL) {
3381 error_msg = "calloc failed";
3382 goto fail;
3383 }
3384
3385 if (hook.calloc_nelem != nelem || hook.calloc_elsize != elsize) {
3386 error_msg = "calloc invalid nelem or elsize";
3387 goto fail;
3388 }
3389
3390 switch(domain)
3391 {
3392 case PYMEM_DOMAIN_RAW: PyMem_RawFree(ptr); break;
3393 case PYMEM_DOMAIN_MEM: PyMem_Free(ptr); break;
3394 case PYMEM_DOMAIN_OBJ: PyObject_Free(ptr); break;
3395 }
3396
3397 Py_INCREF(Py_None);
3398 res = Py_None;
3399 goto finally;
3400
3401fail:
3402 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError, error_msg);
3403
3404finally:
3405 PyMem_SetAllocator(domain, &hook.alloc);
3406 return res;
3407}

3442static int
3443fm_nomemory(void)
3444{
3445 FmData.count++;
3446 if (FmData.count > FmData.start &&
3447 (FmData.stop <= 0 || FmData.count <= FmData.stop)) {

3490static void
3491fm_setup_hooks(void)
3492{
3493 PyMemAllocatorEx alloc;
3494
3495 if (FmHook.installed) {
3496 return;
3497 }
3498 FmHook.installed = 1;
3499
3500 alloc.malloc = hook_fmalloc;
3501 alloc.calloc = hook_fcalloc;
3502 alloc.realloc = hook_frealloc;
3503 alloc.free = hook_ffree;
3504 PyMem_GetAllocator(PYMEM_DOMAIN_RAW, &FmHook.raw);
3505 PyMem_GetAllocator(PYMEM_DOMAIN_MEM, &FmHook.mem);
3506 PyMem_GetAllocator(PYMEM_DOMAIN_OBJ, &FmHook.obj);
3507
3508 alloc.ctx = &FmHook.raw;
3509 PyMem_SetAllocator(PYMEM_DOMAIN_RAW, &alloc);
3510
3511 alloc.ctx = &FmHook.mem;
3512 PyMem_SetAllocator(PYMEM_DOMAIN_MEM, &alloc);
3513

3515 PyMem_SetAllocator(PYMEM_DOMAIN_OBJ, &alloc);

3529static PyObject*
3530set_nomemory(PyObject *self, PyObject *args)
3531{
3532 /* Memory allocation fails after 'start' allocation requests, and until
3533 * 'stop' allocation requests except when 'stop' is negative or equal
3534 * to 0 (default) in which case allocation failures never stop. */
3535 FmData.count = 0;
3536 FmData.stop = 0;
3537 if (!PyArg_ParseTuple(args, "i|i", &FmData.start, &FmData.stop)) {
3538 return NULL;
3539 }
3540 fm_setup_hooks();
3541 Py_RETURN_NONE;
3542}

3548 Py_RETURN_NONE;

3640
3641 PyThread_exit_thread();
3642}
3643
3644static PyObject *
3645call_in_temporary_c_thread(PyObject *self, PyObject *callback)
3646{
3647 PyObject *res = NULL;
3648 test_c_thread_t test_c_thread;
3649 long thread;
3650
3651 PyEval_InitThreads();
3652
3653 test_c_thread.start_event = PyThread_allocate_lock();
3654 test_c_thread.exit_event = PyThread_allocate_lock();
3655 test_c_thread.callback = NULL;
3656 if (!test_c_thread.start_event || !test_c_thread.exit_event) {
3657 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError, "could not allocate lock");
3658 goto exit;
3659 }
3660
3661 Py_INCREF(callback);
3662 test_c_thread.callback = callback;
3663
3664 PyThread_acquire_lock(test_c_thread.start_event, 1);
3665 PyThread_acquire_lock(test_c_thread.exit_event, 1);
3666
3667 thread = PyThread_start_new_thread(temporary_c_thread, &test_c_thread);
3668 if (thread == -1) {
3669 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError, "unable to start the thread");
3670 PyThread_release_lock(test_c_thread.start_event);
3671 PyThread_release_lock(test_c_thread.exit_event);
3672 goto exit;
3673 }
3674
3675 PyThread_acquire_lock(test_c_thread.start_event, 1);
3676 PyThread_release_lock(test_c_thread.start_event);
3677
3678 Py_BEGIN_ALLOW_THREADS
3679 PyThread_acquire_lock(test_c_thread.exit_event, 1);
3680 PyThread_release_lock(test_c_thread.exit_event);
3681 Py_END_ALLOW_THREADS
3682
3683 Py_INCREF(Py_None);
3684 res = Py_None;
3685
3686exit:
3687 Py_CLEAR(test_c_thread.callback);
3688 if (test_c_thread.start_event)
3689 PyThread_free_lock(test_c_thread.start_event);
3690 if (test_c_thread.exit_event)
3691 PyThread_free_lock(test_c_thread.exit_event);
3692 return res;
3693}
3694#endif /* WITH_THREAD */

4072tracemalloc_track(PyObject *self, PyObject *args)
4073{
4074 unsigned int domain;
4075 PyObject *ptr_obj;
4076 void *ptr;
4077 Py_ssize_t size;
4078 int release_gil = 0;
4079 int res;
4080
4081 if (!PyArg_ParseTuple(args, "IOn|i", &domain, &ptr_obj, &size, &release_gil))
4082 return NULL;
4083 ptr = PyLong_AsVoidPtr(ptr_obj);
4084 if (PyErr_Occurred())
4085 return NULL;
4086
4087 if (release_gil) {
4088 Py_BEGIN_ALLOW_THREADS
4089 res = PyTraceMalloc_Track(domain, (uintptr_t)ptr, size);
4090 Py_END_ALLOW_THREADS
4091 }
4092 else {
4093 res = PyTraceMalloc_Track(domain, (uintptr_t)ptr, size);
4094 }
4095
4096 if (res < 0) {
4097 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError, "PyTraceMalloc_Track error");
4098 return NULL;
4099 }
4100
4101 Py_RETURN_NONE;
4102}

4159static PyObject *
4160raise_SIGINT_then_send_None(PyObject *self, PyObject *args)
4161{
4162 PyGenObject *gen;
4163
4164 if (!PyArg_ParseTuple(args, "O!", &PyGen_Type, &gen))
4165 return NULL;
4166
4167 /* This is used in a test to check what happens if a signal arrives just
4168 as we're in the process of entering a yield from chain (see
4169 bpo-30039).
4170
4171 Needs to be done in C, because:
4172 - we don't have a Python wrapper for raise()
4173 - we need to make sure that the Python-level signal handler doesn't run
4174 *before* we enter the generator frame, which is impossible in Python
4175 because we check for signals before every bytecode operation.
4176 */
4177 raise(SIGINT);
4178 return _PyGen_Send(gen, Py_None);
4179}

4183fastcall_args(PyObject *args, PyObject ***stack, Py_ssize_t *nargs)
4184{

4186 *stack = NULL;
4187 *nargs = 0;

4191 *nargs = PyTuple_GET_SIZE(args);
4192 }
4193 else {
4194 PyErr_SetString(PyExc_TypeError, "args must be None or a tuple");
4195 return -1;
4196 }
4197 return 0;
4198}
